President [[Hosni Mubarak]] has ruled Egypt since 1981. His government has been criticised in the media and amongst [[Non-governmental organization|NGOs]]{{Which?|date=January 2011}}. His support for [[Israel]] won him the support of the West and a continuation of hefty annual aid from the United States<ref name="Hosni Mubarak"/>. His government is also noted for its crackdown on Islamic militants.<ref name="Hosni Mubarak">{{cite web|author=|url=http://topics.nytimes.com/top/reference/timestopics/people/m/hosni_mubarak/index.html|title=Hosni Mubarak|publisher=The New York Times|date=2010-03-08 |accessdate=2011-01-25}}</ref> As a result, the initial reactions to Hosni Mubarak's abuses by the U.S. were muted, and most instances of socio-political protest in the country, when they occurred at all, rarely made major news headlines in the United States.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.csmonitor.com/World/Backchannels/2011/0126/The-US-response-to-Egypt-s-protests |title=The US response to Egypt's protests |publisher=CSMonitor.com |date= |accessdate=2011-01-26}}</ref>
